The second step of the [DC upgrade documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/upgrading-confluence-data-center-1507377.html#UpgradingConfluenceDataCenter-6.CopyConfluencetoremainingnodes] mentions this:

{quote}
2. Copy the installation directory and local home directory from the first node to the next node. 
If the path to the local home directory is different on this node, edit the confluence-init.properties to point to the correct location. 
{quote}

We should add another note on this step about the *confluence.cluster.node.name* property that can be configured either in confluence.cfg.xml or setenv.sh files. If the admin just copies the install and home folders to the other notes, the node name will be the same for all of them. This property should be updated manually after copying those directories.

h3. Issue Summary

Confluence allows you to insert Jira issue dates (using default or custom fields) into the Team Calendar by creating an event.

However, if your custom field is configured so that the issue types associated with the default configuration of the custom field is _not_ to all issue types available, then the custom field won't appear in the TC "Create event" dialog.

(!) This only happens if the JQL/filter you use selects more than one project. If you select the projects individually, it works just fine.
h3. Environment
 * Confluence 6.6.13, 6.14.0
 * Jira 7.6.7, 7.7.2, 8.2.1
 * Team Calendar 6.0.27

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create an applink between Jira and Confluence.
 # In Jira, create two projects.
 # Create a custom date field, then associate it with all screens in the two projects.
 # Configure the custom field so that the applicable issue types are just set to one of them (i.e. "Task").
 ** !Custom Field Config - Doesn't work.png|thumbnail!
 # Save the config and create a sample issue (type "Task") in Jira.
 # In Confluence, create a simple Jira Issue Macro on a page to enable OAuth for your user.
 # Create a calendar and try to create an event of type "Jira Issue Dates".
 # Select a single project and you can see the custom field "Release Date" appear.
 ** !Single Project A - Works.png|thumbnail!
 ** !Single Project B - Works.png|thumbnail!
 # Now insert a JQL so that it includes two projects.
{code:java}
project in ("Project One", "Project Two"){code}

h3. Expected Results

The custom field "Release Date" should appear as well.
h3. Actual Results

The custom field "Release Date" doesn't appear when the JQL includes two projects. If you go back to just one project, it works fine.

!Two Projects A and B - Doesn't work.png|thumbnail!
h3. Note

Confluence makes a REST call to obtain the date fields to display in the dialog. For example:
 * {{[http://localhost:8093/conf614/rest/calendar-services/1.0/calendar/jira/c8294f2e-923d-34cf-a218-858f95e7e0d0/date-fields/jql.json?query=project+in+(%22Project+One%22%2C+%22Project+Two%22])}}

The API results don't include the custom field if two projects are in the JQL.
{code:java}
[
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Due Date",
    "key": "duedate"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Version Due Date",
    "key": "versiondue"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Sprints",
    "key": "sprint"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Created Date",
    "key": "created"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Resolved Date",
    "key": "resolution"
  }
]{code}
If I only choose a single project _or_ perform the workaround below (with two projects), the custom field is returned.
{code:java}
[
 {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Due Date",
    "key": "duedate"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Version Due Date",
    "key": "versiondue"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Sprints",
    "key": "sprint"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Created Date",
    "key": "created"
  },
  {
    "customfield": false,
    "name": "Issue Resolved Date",
    "key": "resolution"
  },
  {
    "customfield": true,
    "name": "Release Date",
    "key": "customfield_10200"
  }
]{code}
h3. Workaround
 # Choose only one project in the TC event you're creating.
 # Change the applicable issue types for the custom field's "Default Configuration Scheme" so that it's set to "All issue types" and not specific ones.
 !Custom Field Config - Works.png|thumbnail!

h3. Issue Summary

The cursor for the image hover in TinyMCE 4 has changed from a pointer 'hand' to a move '4 way arrow' which can be quite confusing when using linked images for navigation as the user is not aware it's actually a clickable link.
h3. Environment
 * Confluence 6.14.0 and above
 * TinyMCE 4 in use

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Add an image to a page
 # Attach link to image & publish
 # Hover your mouse over the image
 # Notice the cursor is the 'move' cursor

h3. Expected Results
 * Any link always displays the standard 'pointer' cursor or hand, indicating it's a link


h3. Actual Results
 * All images now show the 'move' cursor, even when a link is included

h3. Notes
 * Whilst this update to Tiny MCE 4 affects all images, it's really the links where this is most problematic
 * The CSS that is causing this is:

{code:java}
.wiki-content img.confluence-embedded-image, .wiki-content img.editor-inline-macro, .wiki-content table.wysiwyg-macro {
    cursor: move;
} {code}
* Previously it referenced, cursor: pointer;

h3. Workaround

Disable TinyMCE 4 editor and rollback to v3:
 # Vist http://<conf-URL>/admin/darkfeatures.action
 # Add *frontend.editor.v4.disable* to the list at the bottom

OR

Add this to the admin Stylesheet
{code:css}
.wiki-content img.confluence-embedded-image, .wiki-content img.editor-inline-macro, .wiki-content table.wysiwyg-macro {
 cursor: pointer !important;
}
{code}
